title: Jeff Van Drew
deleted: In December 2020, Van Drew joined an amicus brief supporting Texas in the Supreme Court case[[Texas_v._Pennsylvania | Texas v. Pennsylvania]], which sought to overturn Trump's loss in Pennsylvania in the 2020 election.<ref>{{cite web | title=Van Drew joins brief seeking delay in finalizing election, Supreme Court says no | website=The Press of Atlantic City | url=https://pressofatlanticcity.com/news/local/van-drew-joins-brief-asking-supreme-court-to-delay-election-results/article_925cb0de-d275-567d-888a-ea39b509b0a7.html | access-date=2020-12-11}}</ref> The case was dismissed.<ref>{{cite web | title=155, ORIG. TEXAS V. PENNSYLVANIA, ET AL. | website=Supreme Court of the United States | url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/121120zr_p860.pdf | access-date=2020-12-11}}</ref> Van Drew later announced his intention to object to the certification of the Electoral College results in Congress.<ref>{{Cite web|last=CNN|first=Manu Raju and Jeremy Herb|title=House Republicans rush to Trump's defense over Georgia call as Democrats prep censure resolution|url=https://www.cnn.com/2021/01/04/politics/trump-call-republican-reaction-censure-resolution/index.html|access-date=2021-01-04|website=CNN}}</ref>
